Analysis on Mueller Report in Twitter¶

Group 12: Ningyan Mao, Yunjia Jiang, Longsheng Yin

Part1: Introduction
¶

The Special Counsel investigation was an investigation of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections and suspicious links between Trump associates and Russian officials, conducted by special prosecutor Robert Mueller from May 2017 to March 2019. It was also called the Russia investigation, the Mueller probe, and the Mueller investigation (Panetta, Grace (January 23, 2019)). The Special Counsel's office concluded its investigation and submitted the final report to Attorney General William Barr on March 22, 2019. The release of the Mueller Report causes a hot discussion on Twitter.

We grabbed the data from twitter API and store the data into our MySQL database after creating a table in it. Our raw data set includes 2,683,444 records and eight columns: Index, Post_Id, Post, Time, User_Id, Location, Followers and Retweeter_Id. Detailed information about data set please see the following section.

We started to collect the data about this report at 12 PM on March 23, 2019, to view the spread of this event on social network and try to find:

  • How does the discussion spread from the time and location dimensions?
  • Who is the most influential person in this discussion?
  • What are the most common hashtags and posts in this discussion?
  • What's people's attitude towards it?

Step 2 : Grab Data¶

We grabbed the data we need from twitter API and store the data into our MySQL database after creating a table in it. By doing so, we got over two million records of tweets about Mueller report within 24 hours.

1. Create a table in MySQL.¶

CREATE TABLE tweets (

id int(11) NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,

post_id varchar(30) DEFAULT NULL,

text text,

date varchar(50) DEFAULT NULL,

user_id varchar(30) DEFAULT NULL,

location varchar(500) DEFAULT NULL,

follwers int(11) DEFAULT NULL,

retwitter_id varchar(30) DEFAULT NULL,
PRIMARY KEY (id)
) ENGINE=InnoDB AUTO_INCREMENT=2578314 DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4;

# set up stream listener
class listener(StreamListener):

    def on_data(self, data):
        all_data = json.loads(data)
# collect all desired data fields 
        if 'text' in all_data:
            post_id = all_data['id_str']
            text = all_data['text']
            date = all_data['created_at']
            user_id = all_data['user']['id_str']
            follwers = all_data['user']['followers_count']
            if all_data["user"]["location"] is None:
                location='NULL'
            else:
                location= all_data["user"]["location"]
            if 'retweeted_status' in all_data:
                retwitter_id=all_data["retweeted_status"]['user']['id_str']
            else:
                retwitter_id= 'NULL'
# insert values into the db
            cursor.execute('INSERT INTO tweets(post_id,text,date,user_id,location,followers,retwitter_id) VALUES (%s,%s,%s,%s,%s,%s,%s)',(post_id,text,date,user_id,location,follwers,retwitter_id))
            conn.commit()
            return True
        else:
            return True

    def on_error(self, status):
        print(status)

auth = OAuthHandler(ckey, csecret)
auth.set_access_token(atoken, asecret)

# create stream and filter on a searchterm
twitterStream = Stream(auth, listener())
twitterStream.filter(track=['mueller','report','trump','donald'], languages = ["en"], stall_warnings = True)

#stop after 24 hours

2. Data Description¶

  • Index: auto-increment index for each record in our dataset.
  • Post_Id: the id for each tweet.
  • Post: the content for each tweet.
  • Time: Greenwich Mean Time (GMT) and date of each tweet.
  • User_Id: id of the user who posts that tweet.
  • Location: the location of the user when posting the tweet.
  • Followers: number of followers for the user who posts the tweet.
  • Retweeter_Id: id of the user of the original post (null if it is not retweeted).

Problems¶

  • 'Index'ï¼šThis column is unnecessary for our following analysis.
  • 'Post'ï¼šThis column has a lot of messy values which cannot be applied by our analysis directly.
  • 'Time'ï¼šThe format of this column is not the ideal one for our analysis.
  • 'Location'ï¼šThis column has a lot of messy values which cannot be applied by our analysis directly and also has plenty of empty values.
  • 'Followers'ï¼šThis column has some empty values and be treated as categorical variable rather than integer.
  • 'Retweeter_Id'ï¼šThis column has a lot of empty values.

In [8]:
regex_str = r"(?:\#+[\w_]+[\w\'_\-]*[\w_]+)" # hash-tags
    
tokens_re = re.compile(r'('+regex_str+')', re.VERBOSE | re.IGNORECASE)
 
def tokenize(s):
    s=str(s)
    return tokens_re.findall(s)
In [9]:
data['Hashtags'] = data['Post'].map(tokenize)
In [10]:
def clean_tweet(tweet):
    tweet = re.sub(r'http\S+', '', tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r"#(\w+)", '', tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r"@(\w+)", '', tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r'[^\w\s\']', '', tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r'[0-9]', '', tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r'RT', '', tweet)
    tweet = tweet.strip().lower()
    return tweet
In [11]:
data['Post'] = data['Post'].astype(str).map(clean_tweet)
  • 'Time'ï¼šConvert the strings into datetime values.

¶

1. The overall pattern of the spread of The release of Muller Report in Twitter.¶

* Volume¶

(1) How does the volume of posts related to this event develop in Twitter by time series?

The volume of posts related to 'Muller Report' developed by the time series.

According to this plot, we find out that the number of posts is relatively low from 3:00 to 12:00 GMT, which is from 23:00 to 8:00 in the US. It is because most people were sleeping.
Except for this, the heat of this event remained high during these 24 hours.

* Retweet Network¶

(1) How do the users who contributed to the spread of this event connect to each other?

Analyze the retweet network by the relation between original posts and retweeted posts.

In [54]:
# Draw network between tweeters and retweeters

(4) Is there relationship between hashtags and conversion rate?

  • Potential reach: number of followers of the targeted account, which is the value under the column 'Followers'.
  • Actual reach: number of retweets received by each post. Create a column : 'Retweets'.
  • Conversion Rate: measured by number of actual reach divided by number of potential reach. Create a column : 'Conversion Rate'. Use it to measure the spread out facilitating of each hashtag.

3. Analyze key words of posts by content.¶

(1) What are the most common phrases during the event spread ?

We used the dataset with location information as a sample of the entire dataset for analyzing.

  • Firstly, we tokenized the words from tweets after deleting the links, hashtags, numbers, punctuations and retweet signs.
  • Secondly, we added meaningless words and commonly used words into 'english' stopwords and removed them from previously tokenized word lists.
  • Thirdly, we lemmatized the words and coverted all the words into a dictionary.
  • Finally, we drew a word cloud to show the most frequently used words.

# remove stop words
def remove_stopwords(text):
    text = [word for word in text if word not in stopword]
    return text
    
data_post['nonstop'] = data_post['tokens'].apply(lambda x: remove_stopwords(x))

WC = defaultdict(int)
for word_id, word_count in itertools.chain.from_iterable(corpus):
    WC[word_id] += word_count

# Create a sorted list from the defaultdict: sorted_word_count
word_counts = sorted(WC.items(), key=lambda w: w[1], reverse=True) 

# Assemble all words with frequencies for Word Cloud
all_words = []
for word_id, word_count in word_counts:
    all_words.extend([D.get(word_id)] * word_count)

4. Sentiment Analysis¶

(1) What is the proportion of sentiments?

We use TextBlob() to do a simple sentiment analysis. We can get three kinds of results, 'Positive', 'Negative' and 'Neutral'. For the reason that original dataframe is too large (over 2.6 million records) to analyze, we use the data_location dataframe, which contains over 150000 records, to get an overview of people's sentiment about this event.

In [93]:
from textblob import TextBlob
In [94]:
def text_sentiment(text):
    analysis=TextBlob(text)
    # set sentiment 
    if analysis.sentiment.polarity > 0: 
        return 'positive'
    elif analysis.sentiment.polarity == 0: 
        return 'neutral'
    else: 
        return 'negative'

(5) How does the sentiment changed by topics?

In [345]:
def format_topics_sentences(ldamodel=None, corpus=corpus, texts=data):
    # Init output
    sent_topics_df = pd.DataFrame()

    # Get main topic in each document
    for i, row_list in enumerate(ldamodel[corpus]):
        row = row_list[0] if ldamodel.per_word_topics else row_list            
        row = sorted(row, key=lambda x: (x[1]), reverse=True)
        # Get the Dominant topic, Perc Contribution and Keywords for each document
        for j, (topic_num, prop_topic) in enumerate(row):
            if j == 0:  # => dominant topic
                wp = ldamodel.show_topic(topic_num)
                sent_topics_df = sent_topics_df.append(pd.Series([int(topic_num), round(prop_topic,4)]), ignore_index=True)
            else:
                break
    sent_topics_df.columns = ['Dominant_Topic', 'Perc_Contribution']

    # Add original text to the end of the output
    contents = pd.Series(texts.map(' '.join))
    sent_topics_df = pd.concat([sent_topics_df, contents], axis=1)
    return(sent_topics_df)

Part4: Conclusion
¶

Summary:¶

From the beginning of the analysis, we try to get a general overview of the spread of Mueller Report on Twitter from the perspectives of time, location(states), population and retweet network.

The volume of posts related to 'Mueller Report' is highly related with time series. The number of posts is fairly low during the night, and remains enough high the following day hours with an average count around 180,000. The top five states behaved most actively during this event are CA, NY, TX, FL, OH. Top four states are states with enough population and developed economy, which contributed to the hot discussion and high level of attention of this event. Interestingly, a mid-west state Ohio ranked highly in the total volume of tweet posts. The reason we found is that the roots of the Mueller Report can be traced to Cleveland. Also, Ohio reaction to special counsel Robert Mueller's report on Russia interference on the 2016 presidential election was split down the political spectrum. There also shows a relationship between time and location in terms of the distribution of posts volume. In CA, people posted tweets immediately when the event happened. While in NY, people's behaviors were the opposite. We guessed the reason behind can be character differences. There appeared two main spread centers: posters who received most retweets. Most of these connections are output by the main nodes in each group. Posters identified into different group seldom retweeted the post of users belong to the other group.

Secondly, we analyze the characteristics of this event by hashtags. States with a tremendous high amount of hashtags are states with higher posting frequency. There is no specific relationship between the number of followers and the hashtags applied frequency. However, high-frequency users know how to post tweets effectively. Another common technique we found is that official accounts tend to apply hashtags to attract followers to retweet and guide public opinions. The first ranking hashtag is '#Topbuzz', which is a breaking news website. Hashtags related with '#Mueller', '#MuellersReport' and '#Trump' also attract high conversion rates.

Thirdly, we analyze the characteristics of this event by posts. From word cloud, we can find that except for common words like 'trump', 'mueller', the most frequently used words are 'democrat', 'people', 'russia' and 'collusion'. Then, we cluster them into several groups to get different subjects. From the TF-IDF and LDA models, we find four main different topics.

What's more, we want to know the sentiment of this event. We find that most people hold a neutral attitude towards this event, and about one third of the tweets related to positive sentiment. Sentiments changed with time, location, and two people whose posts were most retweeted. Tweets posted before 2 am on March 24 have a positive rate below the average, while posted after that have a positive rate above the average. We can find that 9 of 10 states with the highest positive sentiment percentage voted for Trump Donald in 2016. It means that people in states supporting Trump tend to post positive tweets about the Mueller Report. Sensitivity conditions of people who retweeted tweets from two centers of each retweet clusters are significantly different. Most people who retweeted Charlie Kirk's tweet hold negative attitudes. Most people who retweeted James Woods's tweet hold positive attitudes. However, sentiment conditions in different topics are similar, from which we can see the magic of twitterï¼

Insights:¶

At the beginning of the project, we want to learn for the spread of an event how the information flow broadcasts through the whole network, for the certain posts how the hashtags and contents impact the popularity of these posts and for the certain event how the main sentiments of users will be.

Fortunately, we happened to witness a high politically topical eventâ€” the release of Mueller report, so we grasped data from Twitter API for 24 hours and analyzed the spread of this event on the Twitter from network, hashtags, contents these three dimensions.

There are two main points of the meaning of our analysis.

On one hand, by analyzing the release of the Mueller report on Twitter from three aspects: network, hashtags and post contents, we can know this event from various perspectives so that we can have understood the whole event thoroughly. By exploring the structure of the retweet-network, we find that people who are identified in the retweet-network can be divided into two different clusters which are tightly related to the two major users in this retweet-network. The public attitudes of these two users are also different. By analyzing the hashtags and content of posts, we can know how the hashtags influenced the spread of the posts, which hashtags and vocabularies are used most frequently, what the main topics people tweeted, and what the main sentiments of these posts had.

On another hand, our analysis can also be applied in other fields. For the analysis of the retweet-network, we can find who is the most influential person in the spread of this event. This technology may be applied for the promotion of some products on tweets basing on the history data from the promotion of similar products on the Tweeter. The companies can cooperate with the popular tweet users to promote their products. For the sentiment analysis of hashtags and posts, we can understand the influence of the event. This technology can be used by public relations departments. The analysis of the post sentiments may help public relation departments adopt appropriate strategies to reduce the negative impact caused by the event.
